The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 The B.Ed 2006 exams of Calcutta University, under the old syllabus, starts on January 12, controller of examinations O.S. Adhikari said. The tests will continue till February 9. 

 IndiGo, a low-fare domestic carrier, has announced that it has received CAT-III approval from the directorate-general of civil aviation, to operate in foggy weather at Calcutta and other airports. More than 40 per cent of the airlines pilots have been trained to operate in low visibility, said Bruce Ashby, IndiGo president and CEO.

 A three-day international seminar on algorithms and computation is being organised at Indian Statistical Institute from December 18. Computer science experts from institutes from across the country and abroad will take part in the seminar. It will focus on recent developments in algorithms.

 Madan Das, 52, was critically injured after wife Arati allegedly poured boiling water on him at their Baranagar home, on the northern fringes of the city, on Saturday. Police said Madan, a trader, had accused Arati of having an affair with a local youth. Madan has been admitted to a local hospital.

 Parthasarathi Roy, a student of Class IX, died after being knocked down by a truck on Jessore Road, near Madhyamgram, on the northern fringes of the city, on Saturday afternoon. He was taken to a local nursing home, where he died. Police said the truck driver lost control and hit the student before ramming into a roadside tree. The vehicle was impounded but the driver fled. 




